Name: chelsealeecoupe
Comment: @ tinamlaker (part 1) I’m sorry if it seemed like I was dismissing her story. That’s the opposite of what I want to do. My anger is not directed at her or any of the women in the article (I did read it.) I  am a woman. A woman who desires to live through pregnancy should I ever receive that blessing. I am a sister. An aunt. A daughter. A friend. I care about women, not just babies. And it makes me sick seeing the way these women were treated during some of the hardest moments of their lives. I’m angry that women aren’t told the truth about their options when they’re in the middle of unbelievably scary circumstances. I’m angry that medical professionals are neglecting women, whether out of genuine ignorance/misunderstanding of the laws or deliberate malpractice. Women deserve to know their rights. They deserve to know that they are not legally required to sit and wait to die or develop sepsis because of pregnancy complications.

Name: chelsealeecoupe
Comment: @ tinamlaker @ tinamlaker (part 2) I live in Tennessee, a state with some of the strictest prolife laws in the country (as mentioned in the article). And I can tell you with 100% certainty that what happened to these women is not the standard of care for mother or baby. I have women close to me that have experienced scenarios like the ones in this article. When my sister was a week out from her due date with my niece, she developed preeclampsia. They induced and she gave birth to a healthy baby and had no further complications. But a month ago, she developed preeclampsia with my nephew. This time she was six weeks from her due date. They wanted to get her to 36 wks if possible, so they scheduled induction but had her come in every afternoon to monitor and be sure she was not in any danger. Had she been in danger at any time they would have induced and immediately given care to both her and the baby. My other sister is also pregnant and had an ectopic pregnancy scare early on. Had it been necessary, they would have cut the fallopian tube to save her life. Her baby would have tragically died as a result, but not because they killed it, and my sister would be alive. A  friend of mine went to the hospital two years ago because she got very sick near the end of her pregnancy. They ran tests and discovered she had peripartum cardiomyopathy. They performed an emergency c-section so they could begin immediate treatment on her heart. The baby had no complications, but unfortunately my friend passed away about a month later because her heart was too weak to recover. My point is simply that regardless of the situation, the standard of care is always:  deliver the baby if the mother’s life is in danger, and then do whatever possible to save the baby while providing the mother with the treatment she needs. I know it can seem like prolife women don’t care about other women. But we are women too, and never want to see a mom die because of pregnancy complications. Too many women are told the only option they have is to abort or die, and this is simply not the case. It isn’t about saving either/or. It’s giving dignity and care to both/and.

There are 9K leases sitting on the desk because the exploration companies couldn't explore while oil was below $70 a barrel. Above $70 they can make money.
So, now they are starting to explore and drill test holes but that takes time and probably half of those 9K
leases are gonna be dry holes.
